text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LanguageOfTheNacirema]]%0a%0a!Philosophy lesson from BAR%0a%0a:Author: roochis%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe polysemy of the word BAR and its context within Nacirema culture %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aFirst, a long, rigid piece of metal or wood is a BAR. However, you also get drinks at a BAR. To become a lawyer, you must pass the BAR. A chocolate BAR is a delicious treat. My favorite song has a catchy first few BARs. During the height of the COVID-19 pandemic, we were BARred from leaving the country. If you're standing in the sunlight, your face is probably BARred with light. Everyone, BAR a few critics, believe weddings should have an open BAR.  %0a%0aI believe the Nacirema people enjoying grouping which is why "Bar" is often used to reference a chunk or a block of something. This indicates that the Nacirema culture centers around categorization. This could cause conflict between different sub-culture of Nacirema. It could also indicate that the Nacirema often view actions of an individual in context of a larger group. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210327-143536-690480#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Alternate interpretation of "Bar" %0a-> - abbyl%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAn alternate way to consider how the word "bar" reflects Nacireman society is that the Nacirema people seem to think in black and white. For them, there are only two types of things: those that fit a category, and those who do not. For example, the "Bar" is used to describe the test people have to pass in order to become a lawyer. "Bar" only describes a standard for which people are considered to pass, or not pass, and doesn't take into account if a person did particularly well, very poorly, or very close to the cutoff score. Similarly, the phrase "bar a few" means "except", dividing people into a group that fits a category and another group that does not. The phrase doesn't account for having a gray zone at all. Moreover, even "bars" people drink from can be thought of as a divide because people are either behind the bar or in front of the bar.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210327-143536-690480#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: C:)%0a(:Category: LanguageOfTheNacirema:)
