author:1616855735=abbyl
diff:1616855735:1616300383:=47,55c47%0a%3c #foxbegin 210327-143536-690480#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Alternate interpretation of "Bar" %0a%3c -> - abbyl%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c An alternate way to consider how the word "bar" reflects Nacireman society is that the Nacirema people seem to think in black and white. For them, there are only two types of things: those that fit a category, and those who do not. For example, the "Bar" is used to describe the test people have to pass in order to become a lawyer. "Bar" only describes a standard for which people are considered to pass, or not pass, and doesn't take into account if a person did particularly well, very poorly, or very close to the cutoff score. Similarly, the phrase "bar a few" means "except", dividing people into a group that fits a category and another group that does not. The phrase doesn't account for having a gray zone at all. Moreover, even "bars" people drink from can be thought of as a divide because people are either behind the bar or in front of the bar.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210327-143536-690480#%0a---%0a> %0a
